## Test Anti-Pattern Audit — `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **High** | 1 |
| **Medium** | 2 |

This test class is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving ~95% line coverage), but almost nothing is *verified*. These tests will pass even if the production code is wildly broken.

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The entire class follows the pattern: call a method, assert nothing (or only `IsNotNull`). 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**; the remaining 4 use only `Assert.IsNotNull` — which cannot fail for value-returning methods that aren't nullable in practice.

**Affected methods (zero assertions):**

| Test Method | Line |
|---|---|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17 |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 31 |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 39 |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 63 |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 69 |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 85 |

**Fix example — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17):**

```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// AFTER — verifies the product is retrievable with correct state
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_ProductIsRetrievableBysku()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

**Fix example — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 31):**

```csharp
// AFTER — verifies the price actually changed
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_PriceIsUpdatedToNewValue()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
}
```

**Fix example — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69):**

```csharp
// AFTER — verifies discount math
[TestMethod]
public void ApplyBulkDiscount_ReducesPricesByFraction()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 10.00m));
    _catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

    var product = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(9.00m, product?.Price);
}
